# Chrome Extension Best Practices

Follow [Chrome Web Store Best Practices](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/webstore/best-practices/) when changing this extension.

## Manifest and platform

- Use **Manifest V3** only (`manifest_version: 3`). Required for Chrome Web Store.
- Request **minimal permissions**. Prefer `activeTab` over broad host permissions when possible.
- Document each permission in README and in the store listing.

## Performance and bfcache

- **Do not use `unload` or `beforeunload`** in content scripts. They invalidate the back/forward cache and slow down users. Use `pagehide` if you need to run code when the page is hidden, or `chrome.tabs.onRemoved` for when a tab is closed.
- **Do not use WebSockets or WebRTC in content scripts.** They prevent the page from being cached. Move such logic to a background service worker and communicate with the content script via `chrome.runtime.connect` / messaging.

## Security and privacy

- Do not send user data over non-HTTPS. No deceptive installation or behavior.
- **Privacy disclosure**: Keep `PRIVACY.md` accurate. The Chrome Web Store Privacy tab must match: what data is collected, how it is used, and that it is accurate and up to date.
- When adding new permissions or data handling, update `PRIVACY.md` and the store listing.

## User experience

- Keep the UI simple and non-distracting. Persistent UI (e.g. FAB, side panel) should support the task without clutter.
- Do not request sign-in unless necessary; if you do, prefer Sign in with Google and the Chrome Identity API.

## Store listing (when publishing)

- Provide required assets: icon, tile, marquee, screenshots. See [Images of a high-quality listing](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/webstore/best-practices/#provide-great-images).
- Description and listing must clearly state what the extension does.
- Choose the correct category (e.g. Productivity, Education, Developer Tools) per the [category list](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/webstore/best-practices/#choose-your-extensions-category-well).
- Follow [Branding Guidelines](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/webstore/branding/) for name, description, and logo.

## Testing

- Test on multiple Chrome versions and OSs when possible.
- Consider end-to-end tests (e.g. Puppeteer) for critical flows.
- Verify the extension does not break back/forward cache (no unload, no WebSockets in content script).
